--   step-decomposer-*→steps (16 matches), action-decomposer-*→actions (60 matches).

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- OBSERVATIONS
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢= obs-fractal-spawner-scaling
  given §11-fractal-task-planner
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "SPAWNER CHAINS CREATE EXPONENTIAL CELL GROWTH: The 3-level spawner chain (spawn-task-decomposers → spawn-step-decomposers → spawn-action-decomposers) turns 1 goal into 80 dynamically created cells. Each spawner reads its parent level's wildcards and expands: 1 → 4 → 16 → 60. The max bounds (5, 20, 60) are essential safety valves — without them, a 5-subgoal x 5-task x 5-step x 4-action decomposition would create 500+ cells. The max on ⊢⊢ is not just a performance hint; it's a resource contract."

⊢= obs-wildcard-as-synchronization-barrier
  given §11-fractal-task-planner
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "WILDCARDS ACT AS SYNCHRONIZATION BARRIERS: validate-level-2 depends on task-decomposer-*→tasks, which only resolves when ALL 4 task-decomposer cells have frozen. This makes the wildcard a natural barrier: all cells at level N must complete before level N+1 validation runs. Same for spawn-step-decomposers — it reads task-decomposer-*→tasks and waits for all to freeze before spawning. The wildcard is doing double duty: collecting results AND synchronizing levels. This is emergent from the semantics ('ready when ALL matching cells frozen'), not explicit barrier syntax."

⊢= obs-guard-gated-assembly
  given §11-fractal-task-planner
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "GUARD CLAUSES ON ASSEMBLE-PLAN PREVENT PREMATURE ASSEMBLY: In R16, assemble-plan depended on raw outputs and trusted that validations would pass. In v0.2, the guard clauses (validate-level-1→valid where valid = true, etc.) make the constraint structural. If ANY validation had failed (valid = false), the guard would evaluate to false, assemble-plan would be SKIPPED, and its yields would become ⊥. This is defense in depth: the ⊨? retry on validators is the first line (fix the decomposition), and the guard on assembly is the second line (refuse to assemble if unfixable). No 'N/A hack' needed."

⊢= obs-mode-accumulate-is-natural
  given §11-fractal-task-planner
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "ACCUMULATE MODE IS THE NATURAL DEFAULT FOR FRACTAL DECOMPOSITION: All three ⊢⊢ spawners use mode accumulate (the v0.2 default). In this program, replace would be catastrophic — re-firing spawn-task-decomposers would discard previously spawned cells that downstream wildcards already depend on. The accumulate/replace distinction matters most for ⊢∘ evolution loops (where replace makes sense for iterative refinement). For pure decomposition trees, accumulate is the only valid mode. Making it the default was the right call."

⊢= obs-cell-level-vs-file-level-recovery
  given §11-fractal-task-planner
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "TWO-TIER RECOVERY: CELL ⊨? OVERRIDES FILE ⊨? WHERE IT MATTERS: validate-level-1, validate-level-2, and validate-level-3 each have their own ⊨? (retry max 2) because validation failure at any level is recoverable — retry the decomposition. The file-scope ⊨? (retry max 2, exhaustion → error-value(⊥)) catches failures in cells WITHOUT explicit recovery (decompose-goal, task-decomposer-*, etc.). The two-tier system means: validators get targeted retry, everything else gets a safety net. If a task-decomposer exhausts retries, its tasks become ⊥, the wildcard collects ⊥, validate-level-2 sees incomplete data, and the guard on assemble-plan blocks assembly. Graceful degradation."

⊢= obs-fractal-self-similarity
  given §11-fractal-task-planner
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "THE FRACTAL PATTERN IS GENUINELY SELF-SIMILAR: Each level repeats the same 3-cell motif: decompose → validate → spawn-next-level. Level 1: decompose-goal → validate-level-1 → spawn-task-decomposers. Level 2: task-decomposer-* → validate-level-2 → spawn-step-decomposers. Level 3: step-decomposer-* → validate-level-3 → spawn-action-decomposers. Level 4: action-decomposer-* → validate-level-4 → [terminal]. The motif IS the fractal unit. A more ambitious version could use ⊢∘ to make this recursive — a single decompose/validate/spawn template that references itself via § quotation. Cell's spawner + wildcard + quotation combo is sufficient to express recursive decomposition."

⊢= obs-confluence-at-scale
  given §11-fractal-task-planner
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "CONFLUENCE ENABLES MASSIVE PARALLELISM: At frame 27, 60 action-decomposer cells enter the ready set simultaneously. Confluence guarantees they can all run in parallel — or in any order — with identical results. For a real Cell runtime, this means: level 4 decomposition is embarrassingly parallel. 60 independent LLM calls. The only serialization points are the spawners (which must see the prior level's wildcards) and the validators (which must see the current level's wildcards). Between those barriers, everything is parallel. The 90-frame serial trace is a presentation artifact; a parallel runtime could complete in roughly 12 barrier-separated waves."
